& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Treatment of breast lesions has evolved toward the use of less-invasive or minimally invasive techniques. Minimally invasive treatments destroy focal groups of cells without surgery; hence, less anesthesia is required, better cosmetic outcomes are achieved because of minimal (if any) scarring, and recovery times are shorter. These techniques include cryoablation, radiofrequency ablation, microwave ablation, high-intensity focused US, laser therapy, vacuum-assisted excision, and irreversible electroporation. Each modality involves the use of different mechanisms and requires specific considerations for application. To date, only cryoablation and vacuum-assisted excision have received U.S. Food and Drug Administration approval for treatment of fibroadenomas and have been implemented as part of the treatment algorithm by the American Society of Breast Surgeons. Several clinical studies on this topic have been performed on outcomes in patients with breast cancer who were treated with these techniques. The results are promising, with more data for radiofrequency ablation and cryoablation available than for other minimally invasive methods for treatment of early-stage breast cancer. Clinical decisions should be made on a case-by-case basis, according to the availability of the technique. MRI is the most effective imaging modality for postprocedural follow-up, with the pattern of enhancement differentiating residual or recurrent disease from postprocedural changes.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.va.jpeg" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200156">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200156">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic" aria-label="US-guided cryoablation technique. (a, b)US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in a) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in b). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. (c, d) US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig1a.jpeg" height="1199" width="1200" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. US-guided cryoablation technique. <b>(a, b)</b> US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in <b>a</b>) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. <b>(c, d)</b> US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="US-guided cryoablation technique. (a, b)US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in a) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in b). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. (c, d) US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig1b.jpeg" height="1233" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. US-guided cryoablation technique. <b>(a, b)</b> US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in <b>a</b>) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. <b>(c, d)</b> US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic" aria-label="US-guided cryoablation technique. (a, b)US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in a) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in b). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. (c, d) US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig1c.jpeg" height="1233" width="1234" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. US-guided cryoablation technique. <b>(a, b)</b> US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in <b>a</b>) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. <b>(c, d)</b> US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic" aria-label="US-guided cryoablation technique. (a, b)US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in a) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in b). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. (c, d) US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle (d)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig1d.jpeg" height="1233" width="1233" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. US-guided cryoablation technique. <b>(a, b)</b> US images show the cryoprobe inserted through the geometric center of the mass (*) and parallel to its long axis. The cryoprobe extends beyond the margin of the mass (double-headed arrow in <b>a</b>) to center the mass in the ice ball as the treatment cycles proceed. Ideally the mass should be greater than 1 cm deep from the skin surface to protect against thermal injury to the skin (double-headed arrow in <b>b</b>). Hydrodissection has been used in superficial masses to protect against skin injury. <b>(c, d)</b> US images show guided monitoring of the size of the ice ball, with an adequate ice ball diameter of approximately twice that of the tumor after the second freeze cycle <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 estrogen receptor–positive (ER+) progesterone receptor–positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor 2–negative (HER2−) invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the left breast in a 73-year-old woman. (a) Preablation craniocaudal view (left) and spot compression view (top right) mammograms show a spiculated irregular mass (circle) 10 cm from the nipple. US image (bottom right) shows an irregular hypoechoic mass (arrow). (b, c) Postcryoablation follow-up mammograms acquired at 6 (b) and 18 (c) months show fat necrosis, a decrease in density, and an interval reduction in size. Note that the biopsy clip (arrow) in the cryoablation site serves as an important landmark for postablation follow-up."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig2a.jpeg" height="1970" width="2100" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Grade 2 estrogen receptor–positive (ER+) progesterone receptor–positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor 2–negative (HER2−) invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the left breast in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Preablation craniocaudal view (left) and spot compression view (top right) mammograms show a spiculated irregular mass (circle) 10 cm from the nipple. US image (bottom right) shows an irregular hypoechoic mass (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Postcryoablation follow-up mammograms acquired at 6 <b>(b)</b> and 18 <b>(c)</b> months show fat necrosis, a decrease in density, and an interval reduction in size. Note that the biopsy clip (arrow) in the cryoablation site serves as an important landmark for postablation follow-up.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 estrogen receptor–positive (ER+) progesterone receptor–positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor 2–negative (HER2−) invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the left breast in a 73-year-old woman. (a) Preablation craniocaudal view (left) and spot compression view (top right) mammograms show a spiculated irregular mass (circle) 10 cm from the nipple. US image (bottom right) shows an irregular hypoechoic mass (arrow). (b, c) Postcryoablation follow-up mammograms acquired at 6 (b) and 18 (c) months show fat necrosis, a decrease in density, and an interval reduction in size. Note that the biopsy clip (arrow) in the cryoablation site serves as an important landmark for postablation follow-up."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig2b.jpeg" height="1430" width="795" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Grade 2 estrogen receptor–positive (ER+) progesterone receptor–positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor 2–negative (HER2−) invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the left breast in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Preablation craniocaudal view (left) and spot compression view (top right) mammograms show a spiculated irregular mass (circle) 10 cm from the nipple. US image (bottom right) shows an irregular hypoechoic mass (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Postcryoablation follow-up mammograms acquired at 6 <b>(b)</b> and 18 <b>(c)</b> months show fat necrosis, a decrease in density, and an interval reduction in size. Note that the biopsy clip (arrow) in the cryoablation site serves as an important landmark for postablation follow-up.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 estrogen receptor–positive (ER+) progesterone receptor–positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor 2–negative (HER2−) invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the left breast in a 73-year-old woman. (a) Preablation craniocaudal view (left) and spot compression view (top right) mammograms show a spiculated irregular mass (circle) 10 cm from the nipple. US image (bottom right) shows an irregular hypoechoic mass (arrow). (b, c) Postcryoablation follow-up mammograms acquired at 6 (b) and 18 (c) months show fat necrosis, a decrease in density, and an interval reduction in size. Note that the biopsy clip (arrow) in the cryoablation site serves as an important landmark for postablation follow-up."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig2c.jpeg" height="1430" width="792" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Grade 2 estrogen receptor–positive (ER+) progesterone receptor–positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor 2–negative (HER2−) invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) of the left breast in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Preablation craniocaudal view (left) and spot compression view (top right) mammograms show a spiculated irregular mass (circle) 10 cm from the nipple. US image (bottom right) shows an irregular hypoechoic mass (arrow). <b>(b, c)</b> Postcryoablation follow-up mammograms acquired at 6 <b>(b)</b> and 18 <b>(c)</b> months show fat necrosis, a decrease in density, and an interval reduction in size. Note that the biopsy clip (arrow) in the cryoablation site serves as an important landmark for postablation follow-up.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic" aria-label="Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. (a) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. (b) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. (c, d) PET/CT (c) and PET (d) images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (18F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig3a.jpeg" height="1005" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. <b>(c, d)</b> PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and PET <b>(d)</b> images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (<sup>18</sup>F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. (a) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. (b) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. (c, d) PET/CT (c) and PET (d) images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (18F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig3b.jpeg" height="918" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. <b>(c, d)</b> PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and PET <b>(d)</b> images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (<sup>18</sup>F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. (a) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. (b) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. (c, d) PET/CT (c) and PET (d) images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (18F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig3c.jpeg" height="918" width="1235" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. <b>(c, d)</b> PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and PET <b>(d)</b> images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (<sup>18</sup>F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic" aria-label="Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. (a) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. (b) Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. (c, d) PET/CT (c) and PET (d) images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (18F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig3d.jpeg" height="918" width="1236" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Biopsy-proven grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma measuring 1.4 cm in a 74-year-old woman who was not considered a candidate for surgery because of multiple medical comorbidities. The patient also underwent microwave ablation of non–small-cell lung cancer in the left upper lobe (not shown), which prompted PET/CT staging and follow-up. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image shows the enhancing cancer (circle). The patient underwent cryoablation. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced maximum intensity projection MR image 6 months after cryoablation shows mild peripheral enhancement (circle), which is likely related to inflammation and fat necrosis. No suspicious component is visualized. <b>(c, d)</b> PET/CT <b>(c)</b> and PET <b>(d)</b> images acquired at 6 months after cryoablation show fluorine 18 (<sup>18</sup>F) fluorodeoxyglucose (FDG) avidity at the periphery (circle), which corresponds to the mild peripheral enhancement at MRI. The FDG avidity and enhancement resolved at subsequent imaging 12 months after cryoablation (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. (a, b) Mammogram (a) and contrast-enhanced MR image (b) show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram.(c, d) Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in c) and 12 months (crosshairs in d) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. (e) Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. (f) Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig4a.jpeg" height="1716" width="880" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammogram <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in <b>c</b>) and 12 months (crosshairs in <b>d</b>) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. <b>(e)</b> Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. <b>(f)</b> Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. (a, b) Mammogram (a) and contrast-enhanced MR image (b) show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram.(c, d) Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in c) and 12 months (crosshairs in d) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. (e) Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. (f) Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig4b.jpeg" height="1716" width="880" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammogram <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in <b>c</b>) and 12 months (crosshairs in <b>d</b>) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. <b>(e)</b> Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. <b>(f)</b> Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. (a, b) Mammogram (a) and contrast-enhanced MR image (b) show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram.(c, d) Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in c) and 12 months (crosshairs in d) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. (e) Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. (f) Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig4c.jpeg" height="1716" width="1144" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammogram <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in <b>c</b>) and 12 months (crosshairs in <b>d</b>) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. <b>(e)</b> Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. <b>(f)</b> Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. (a, b) Mammogram (a) and contrast-enhanced MR image (b) show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram.(c, d) Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in c) and 12 months (crosshairs in d) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. (e) Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. (f) Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig4d.jpeg" height="1620" width="1163" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammogram <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in <b>c</b>) and 12 months (crosshairs in <b>d</b>) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. <b>(e)</b> Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. <b>(f)</b> Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4e" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. (a, b) Mammogram (a) and contrast-enhanced MR image (b) show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram.(c, d) Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in c) and 12 months (crosshairs in d) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. (e) Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. (f) Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig4e.jpeg" height="1620" width="914" aria-labelledby="fig4e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4e</span>. Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammogram <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in <b>c</b>) and 12 months (crosshairs in <b>d</b>) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. <b>(e)</b> Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. <b>(f)</b> Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig4e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4f" class="graphic" aria-label="Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. (a, b) Mammogram (a) and contrast-enhanced MR image (b) show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram.(c, d) Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in c) and 12 months (crosshairs in d) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. (e) Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. (f) Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig4f.jpeg" height="1620" width="1620" aria-labelledby="fig4f" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4f</span>. Grade 2 ER+/PR+ HER2– IDC measuring 1.1 cm in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mammogram <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced MR image <b>(b)</b> show an irregular mass (arrow), which is consistent with the appearance of a known malignancy. Note the biopsy clip in the center of the mass on the mammogram. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced MR images of the breast show a new irregular enhancing mass at the margin of the cryoablation zone at 6 months (circle in <b>c</b>) and 12 months (crosshairs in <b>d</b>) after cryoablation, which is suspicious for recurrence. <b>(e)</b> Mammogram acquired at 12 months after cryoablation shows a round irregular mass (circle) corresponding to the MRI finding. The patient underwent MRI-guided biopsy. <b>(f)</b> Low- to medium-power photomicrograph shows IDC (arrow) at the margin of the postcryoablation change (red line), above which there is fibrosis and a fibroblastic reaction. (Hematoxylin-eosin stain; original magnification, ×10.) (Case courtesy of Yihong Wang, MD, PhD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig4f">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Follow-up mammograms acquired after cryoablation in two patients. Mammograms in a 73-year-old woman (a) and a 91-year-old woman (b) show development of nodular asymmetry in the ablation zone (oval). Note the biopsy clip in the center of each ablation zone, marking the respective site of each ablated cancer. Biopsy was performed in both patients for further evaluation of the new nodular asymmetry. The results of the pathologic examination were consistent with recurrence in the patient in a and with fat necrosis in the patient in b. Patients with imaging findings suspicious for malignancy at follow-up examinations should undergo biopsy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig5a.jpeg" height="1069" width="1604" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Follow-up mammograms acquired after cryoablation in two patients. Mammograms in a 73-year-old woman <b>(a)</b> and a 91-year-old woman <b>(b)</b> show development of nodular asymmetry in the ablation zone (oval). Note the biopsy clip in the center of each ablation zone, marking the respective site of each ablated cancer. Biopsy was performed in both patients for further evaluation of the new nodular asymmetry. The results of the pathologic examination were consistent with recurrence in the patient in <b>a</b> and with fat necrosis in the patient in <b>b</b>. Patients with imaging findings suspicious for malignancy at follow-up examinations should undergo biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic" aria-label="Follow-up mammograms acquired after cryoablation in two patients. Mammograms in a 73-year-old woman (a) and a 91-year-old woman (b) show development of nodular asymmetry in the ablation zone (oval). Note the biopsy clip in the center of each ablation zone, marking the respective site of each ablated cancer. Biopsy was performed in both patients for further evaluation of the new nodular asymmetry. The results of the pathologic examination were consistent with recurrence in the patient in a and with fat necrosis in the patient in b. Patients with imaging findings suspicious for malignancy at follow-up examinations should undergo biopsy."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig5b.jpeg" height="1069" width="1346" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Follow-up mammograms acquired after cryoablation in two patients. Mammograms in a 73-year-old woman <b>(a)</b> and a 91-year-old woman <b>(b)</b> show development of nodular asymmetry in the ablation zone (oval). Note the biopsy clip in the center of each ablation zone, marking the respective site of each ablated cancer. Biopsy was performed in both patients for further evaluation of the new nodular asymmetry. The results of the pathologic examination were consistent with recurrence in the patient in <b>a</b> and with fat necrosis in the patient in <b>b</b>. Patients with imaging findings suspicious for malignancy at follow-up examinations should undergo biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic" aria-label="US guidance for accurate placement of the RFA electrode in the geometric center of the tumor. A, Longitudinal US image shows the tip of the single-needle RFA electrode in contact with the tumor. B, Postdeployment longitudinal US image shows the single-needle electrode traversing the central portion of the tumor. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 29.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig6.jpeg" height="2154" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span>. US guidance for accurate placement of the RFA electrode in the geometric center of the tumor. <i>A</i>, Longitudinal US image shows the tip of the single-needle RFA electrode in contact with the tumor. <i>B</i>, Postdeployment longitudinal US image shows the single-needle electrode traversing the central portion of the tumor. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r29" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r29">29</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7" class="graphic" aria-label="RFA of an invasive breast carcinoma near the chest wall. A, Sagittal contrast-enhanced MR image before RFA shows a 0.9-cm irregular mass (circle) with marked enhancement 1 cm from the pectoralis major muscle. B, Sagittal post-RFA (3 months) contrast-enhanced image, and, C, subtraction MR image show no residual enhancement of the tumor (arrows), and linear peripheral enhancement shows a large ablation volume. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 29.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig7.jpeg" height="1752" width="2999" aria-labelledby="fig7" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7</span>. RFA of an invasive breast carcinoma near the chest wall. <i>A</i>, Sagittal contrast-enhanced MR image before RFA shows a 0.9-cm irregular mass (circle) with marked enhancement 1 cm from the pectoralis major muscle. <i>B</i>, Sagittal post-RFA (3 months) contrast-enhanced image, and, <i>C</i>, subtraction MR image show no residual enhancement of the tumor (arrows), and linear peripheral enhancement shows a large ablation volume. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r29" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r29">29</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig7">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic" aria-label="Successful RFA of IDC without a residual lesion. A, Craniocaudal, and, B, mediolateral oblique mammograms show a mass (arrows) with irregular margins in the upper outer quadrant of the right breast measuring 2.3 cm. C, Sagittal contrast-enhanced, and, D, subtraction MR images obtained before RFA show an avidly enhancing spiculated mass (arrows) measuring 2.6 cm. E, Sagittal contrast-enhanced, and, F, subtraction MR images obtained 2 weeks after RFA show linear peripheral enhancement delineating the ablation zone (arrowheads) and a lack of central enhancement, which confirms that there is no residual tumor. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 29.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig8.jpeg" height="3972" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Successful RFA of IDC without a residual lesion. <i>A</i>, Craniocaudal, and, <i>B</i>, mediolateral oblique mammograms show a mass (arrows) with irregular margins in the upper outer quadrant of the right breast measuring 2.3 cm. <i>C</i>, Sagittal contrast-enhanced, and, <i>D</i>, subtraction MR images obtained before RFA show an avidly enhancing spiculated mass (arrows) measuring 2.6 cm. <i>E</i>, Sagittal contrast-enhanced, and, <i>F</i>, subtraction MR images obtained 2 weeks after RFA show linear peripheral enhancement delineating the ablation zone (arrowheads) and a lack of central enhancement, which confirms that there is no residual tumor. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r29" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r29">29</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9" class="graphic" aria-label="Residual lesion after RFA of an IDC. A, Mediolateral oblique mammogram shows an irregular mass in the upper outer quadrant of the right breast that measures 1.5 cm (arrow). B, US image shows an RFA electrode (arrowheads) positioned in the center of the 1.8-cm hypoechoic mass, with posterior acoustic shadowing. C, D, Sagittal contrast-enhanced MR image obtained before RFA shows a 2.2-cm mass with spiculated margins and marked enhancement (circle in C ), which is also seen on a subtraction image (circle in D). E, Sagittal contrast-enhanced subtraction MR image before RFA, and, F, sagittal contrast-enhanced magnification MR image acquired 2 weeks after RFA show a persistent irregular focus of enhancement near the pectoralis major muscle (arrows) that is compatible with residual tumor. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 29.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig9.jpeg" height="4178" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig9" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span>. Residual lesion after RFA of an IDC. <i>A</i>, Mediolateral oblique mammogram shows an irregular mass in the upper outer quadrant of the right breast that measures 1.5 cm (arrow). <i>B</i>, US image shows an RFA electrode (arrowheads) positioned in the center of the 1.8-cm hypoechoic mass, with posterior acoustic shadowing. <i>C, D,</i> Sagittal contrast-enhanced MR image obtained before RFA shows a 2.2-cm mass with spiculated margins and marked enhancement (circle in <i>C</i>), which is also seen on a subtraction image (circle in <i>D</i>). <i>E</i>, Sagittal contrast-enhanced subtraction MR image before RFA, and, <i>F,</i> sagittal contrast-enhanced magnification MR image acquired 2 weeks after RFA show a persistent irregular focus of enhancement near the pectoralis major muscle (arrows) that is compatible with residual tumor. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r29" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r29">29</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig9">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic" aria-label="Microwave ablation of a breast lesion. A, Conventional US image obtained before ablation. B, Color Doppler, and, C, contrast-enhanced (left) and noncontrast (right) US images acquired immediately after ablation show incomplete ablation. D, Conventional US image immediately after supplementary ablation; E, color Doppler US image at 3 months; and, F, conventional US image at 12 months after supplementary ablation show that the lesion continued to shrink during follow-up. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 44.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig10.jpeg" height="1686" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Microwave ablation of a breast lesion. <i>A</i>, Conventional US image obtained before ablation. <i>B</i>, Color Doppler, and, <i>C</i>, contrast-enhanced (left) and noncontrast (right) US images acquired immediately after ablation show incomplete ablation. <i>D</i>, Conventional US image immediately after supplementary ablation; <i>E</i>, color Doppler US image at 3 months; and, <i>F</i>, conventional US image at 12 months after supplementary ablation show that the lesion continued to shrink during follow-up. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r44" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r44">44</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic" aria-label="US-guided HIFU of a breast fibroadenoma. A, Transverse US image shows a 20-mm fibroadenoma (dotted line) that is located between the inferior quadrants of the left breast. B, US image shows that the system automatically generates the sonications (white lines) to cover the entire volume of the target tissue after the skin line (red line) and fibroadenoma borders (blue outline) are manually defined. C, US follow-up image at 3 months shows a 50% reduction in the size of the fibroadenoma (blue dotted line), a 10-mm reduction in maximum diameter. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 53.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig11.jpeg" height="948" width="3785" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. US-guided HIFU of a breast fibroadenoma. <i>A</i>, Transverse US image shows a 20-mm fibroadenoma (dotted line) that is located between the inferior quadrants of the left breast. <i>B</i>, US image shows that the system automatically generates the sonications (white lines) to cover the entire volume of the target tissue after the skin line (red line) and fibroadenoma borders (blue outline) are manually defined. <i>C</i>, US follow-up image at 3 months shows a 50% reduction in the size of the fibroadenoma (blue dotted line), a 10-mm reduction in maximum diameter. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r53" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r53">53</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI-guided HIFU of breast fibroadenoma. A, Axial gadolinium-enhanced subtraction three-dimensional gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a small rounded nodule of IDC between the upper quadrants of the left breast (arrow). B, Sagittal T1-weighted MR image shows the predicted ultrasound beam path (green triangles) with the planned sonications (green boxes). C, Sagittal T1-weighted MR image acquired after MRI-guided HIFU shows the ablated area, without residual cancer enhancement (arrow). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 53.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig12.jpeg" height="1024" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. MRI-guided HIFU of breast fibroadenoma. <i>A</i>, Axial gadolinium-enhanced subtraction three-dimensional gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a small rounded nodule of IDC between the upper quadrants of the left breast (arrow). <i>B</i>, Sagittal T1-weighted MR image shows the predicted ultrasound beam path (green triangles) with the planned sonications (green boxes). <i>C</i>, Sagittal T1-weighted MR image acquired after MRI-guided HIFU shows the ablated area, without residual cancer enhancement (arrow). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r53" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r53">53</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13" class="graphic" aria-label="MRI of the breast before and after laser ablation. A, Coronal gadolinium-enhanced fat-suppressed MR image acquired before ablation shows an 11-mm grade 1 IDC (arrow). B, Coronal MR image obtained 28 days after percutaneous laser ablation shows the ablation zone with no enhancement at the site of the cancer (arrow). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 76.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200156/asset/images/large/rg.2021200156.fig13.jpeg" height="1339" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig13" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span>. MRI of the breast before and after laser ablation. <i>A</i>, Coronal gadolinium-enhanced fat-suppressed MR image acquired before ablation shows an 11-mm grade 1 IDC (arrow). <i>B</i>, Coronal MR image obtained 28 days after percutaneous laser ablation shows the ablation zone with no enhancement at the site of the cancer (arrow). (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r76" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r76">76</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200156&amp;id=fig13">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kaufman CS, Littrup PJ, Freman-Gibb LA, et al. Office-based cryoablation of breast fibroadenomas: 12-month followup. <em>J Am Coll Surg</em> 2004;198(6):914–923.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jamcollsurg.2004.02.014">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15194073/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-